An initial solution might be;
```cpp
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& nums) {
      if (1 < nums.size()) {
        auto pos = nums.end() - 1;
        do {
          if (*pos > *(pos - 1)) {
            auto dest = pos - 1;
            // Find the first element that is greater then dest, this will be
            // the element between [pos, nums.end()] that is just above dest
            // Use the fact that [pos, nums.end()] is sorted in descending order to do a binary search
            auto target = --std::lower_bound(pos, nums.end(), *dest, std::greater<int>());

            // [2, 4, 3, 1] -> [3, 4, 2, 1]
            std::iter_swap(dest, target);

            // At this point [pos, end) will be sorted descending, we need it to be
            // ascending
            // [3, 4, 2, 1] -> [3, 1, 2, 4] 
            std::reverse(pos, nums.end());
            return;
          }
        } 
        while (--pos != nums.begin());

        // At the end of the permutation, reverse everything.
        std::reverse(nums.begin(), nums.end());
      }
    }
```		
Of course, you could cheat and do
```cpp
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& nums) {
      std::next_permutation(nums.begin(), nums.end());
    }
```
But where's the fun in that?

Can we do better though? Well all we're really trying to do is find the first point where the ordering is no longer ascending when moving right to left. There's an ~~app~~ algorithm for that! `std::is_sorted_until` will return the iterator of the first unsorted element, so using the reverse iterators to search from right to left, we get a one-liner to find the destination element.

```cpp
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& nums) {
      // Find the first point where the ordering from right to left is not sorted
      auto dest = std::is_sorted_until(nums.rbegin(), nums.rend());
      if (dest != nums.rend()) {
        // We found a point, find a candidate to swap with. The range [rbegin, dest) is sorted ascendingly
        // so we can binary search for the first element greater than our destination
        auto target = std::upper_bound(nums.rbegin(), dest, *dest);

        // [2, 4, 3, 1] -> [3, 4, 2, 1]
        std::iter_swap(dest, target);
      }
      // Reverse everything to the right of our dest point. In the case of not being the whole vector this
      // reverses the ordering from being ascending (left to right) to being descending
      // [3, 4, 2, 1] -> [3, 1, 2, 4]
      std::reverse(nums.rbegin(), dest);
    }
```		
