solutions.content:
### Approach: (Without 1 liner XD)

Let us start by taking an example of test case = [1 , 2 , 4 , 3]

Lexicographically next permutation would be [1 , 3 , 2 , 4]. 

Here, we have done 2 things:
- Swapped 2 with 3.
- Sorted the array after the swapped index.

So precisely, the generalised approach, which comes here in mind is:

- Find the index from where we have to swap its value with its next greater value. For this, start from last, just find the index where number is greater than its next index. Say this index as small. 
- Find the index of number, just greater than the number at the small.
- Swap the both values. And sort the array after the swapped index.

Edge case: If array is in descending order, then we have to just sort it to ascending.

My submission:
```
class Solution {
public:
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& number) {
        int i = 0;
        for(i = number.size() - 1 ; i > 0; i--){        //Finding the index needed to be swapped.
            if(number[i] > number[i - 1]){
                break;
            }
        }
        if(i == 0){     
            reverse(number.begin() , number.end());     // Permutation is in descending order. Sort it to ascending order.
        } else {
            int x = number[i - 1], small = i;           
            for(int j = i + 1; j < number.size(); j++){     //Finding the number just greater than at index needed to be swapped.
                if(number[j] > x && number[j] <= number[small]){
                    small = j;
                }
            }

            swap(number[i - 1] , number[small]);        //Swapping the numbers.

            sort(number.begin() + i, number.end());     // Sorting the array after the swapped index.
        }
    }
};
```
