# Intuition
In dictionary consider the names `sam`, `sai` and `sui`. `sai` would be exactly next to sam because it has **`longest prefix match -sa`**. Similarly `sui` will be after `sam` but exactly not after `sam` because it has **`smaller prefix match - s`**. So the permutation with longest prefix match has higher chances of being the next one.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. **Find the breaking index :** 
      - Breaking index occurs when a dip point is observered in the
        pattern of the nums.

        ![next permutation1.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2c0a6174-3062-4837-be9d-6e1454b59591_1682771631.79299.jpeg)
      - `Base codition` occurs when there is no breaking point, this indicates the given nums array is the last permutation. Hence, `reverse` the nums array which gives us our next permutation.

        ![next permutation2.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/15cdbcdd-5553-455c-8a9c-a1cd41272202_1682771975.8683147.jpeg)

1. **Finding num just greater than breaking idx :**
    - Traverse the nums array `n-1 to idx`, if `nums[i] > nums[idx]->swap`and exit the loop.

    ![next permutation3.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0be1c019-bd65-4bb9-9be2-cd98f6fda16b_1682772625.132264.jpeg)

1. **Reverse the remaining nums array :**
    - Reversing is needed because we need the just next Permutation.

    ![next permutation4.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f20a7a5d-5af7-44c2-9095-f303b961b718_1682772824.645866.jpeg)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
      $$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
      $$O(1)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public void nextPermutation(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        // store the breaking point
        int idx = -1;

        for(int i = n-2 ; i>=0 ; i--) {
            if(nums[i] < nums[i+1]) {
                idx = i;
                break;
            }
        }

        // base case - no breakpoint found
        if(idx == -1) {
            Arrays.sort(nums, 0, n);
            return;
        }


        // finding the greater but closest num
        for(int i=n-1 ; i>idx ; i--) {
            if(nums[i] > nums[idx]) {
                int temp = nums[i];
                nums[i] = nums[idx];
                nums[idx] = temp;
                break;
            }
        }
        // Reversing the remaining array.
        Arrays.sort(nums, idx+1, n);
    }
}
```

