/* The simple intution to solve this problem is to find the index which will get swaped.
Now if we dont find any index, that means that the vector is in descending order and 
hence we must sort it in ascending order and return. Now the simple logic to find the 
swap index is that it is the number which breaks the ascending order sequence from the right (nums[i-1] < nums[i]) .
Ex:- 2543, so here 543 is in ascending order from right and 2 breaks the sequence. So 0 will be the swap index. 
Now to get the next permutation and not any permutation, we must swap the index found previously
with the first element which is greater than the nums[index]. Now we swap the 
two elements. So our swap index now contains an element which is greater than what
it had earlier. So now to have the next permutation, we must sort all the elements to its
right in ascending order as it will become the minimum possible value that could have
been formed by replacing the swap index with some value greater than it. 

				Please upvote, if you find the solution helpful. 
*/


class Solution {
public:
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& nums) {
        int index = -1;
        for(int i = nums.size()-1; i>=1; i--)
        {
            if(nums[i-1] < nums[i])
            {
                index = i-1;
                break;
            }
        }

        if(index == -1)
        {
            sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
            return;
        }

        for(int i = nums.size()-1; i>index; i--)
        {
            if(nums[i] > nums[index])
            {
                swap(nums[i], nums[index]);
                sort(nums.begin()+index+1, nums.end());
                return;
            }
        }
    }
};
```

