By observing, we can use DFS to solve the problem. DFS is extremely useful on problems like permutation combination etc..

When we trying to solve a problem with Depth First Search (backtracking), it is useful for us to generate a recursion tree and speaks out the meaning of each level and each branches.

In this particular problem, each level representing a particular subproblems where s[0...level - 1] has already formed valid palindrome partition. The subproblem becomes solving the following s[level...end] subproblems. In the subproblems, we iterate index i from the current level index to the end of the string, if we see s[level...i] is a palindrome, then we can add the current substring s[level...i] to the list and going to the next subproblems s[i+1...end] by recursive call with updated parameter. 

Following the analysis, we can see that there are O(n!) levels of node in the recursive tree, and there are at most n level of recursion on the call stack. 

Then, the problem becomes how to check a string is palindrome. A Naive but working solution is to iterate the string with two pointers walking in the opposite direction:

```
boolean isPalindrome(String s, int start, int end) {
	while (start < end) {
		if (s.charAt(start++) != s.charAt(end--)) {
			return false;
		}
	}
}
```

By taking this method we need O(n) time to check whether a substring s[i...j] is palindrome by calling isPalindrome(s, i, j).
The total time complexity is O(n!*n).
Since there are at most O(n) recursive calls on the call stack and no extra data structure is allocated, space complexity O(n).

However, I noticed that the palindrome problem can be solved by dynamic programming by the following observation:
1. The big problem (string) can be divided into smaller problem (substring or even characters)
2. The minimum sized problems (a single character) have identical or similar properties. 

Above observation implies that using dynamic programming would be a choice. All we need to do is to figure out the base case and induction rules of the problem.

base case: dp[i][i] -> true (a single character is palindrome)
induction rule: 
		dp[i][j] representing whether s[i...j] is a palindrome
		dp[i][j] = true if s[i] == s[j] and s[i], s[j] is next to each other (i - j < 2), 
						or s[i] == s[j] and the subproblem s[i+1...j-1] is a valid palindrome (dp[i+1][j-1])

with the following dp relation we can take O(n^2) time and O(n^2) space to build up the memory:

```
private boolean[][] generateMap(String s) {
	boolean[][] map = new boolean[s.length()][s.length()];
	for (int i = s.length() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
		for (int j = i; j < s.length(); j++) {
			map[i][j] = (s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(j) && (j - i <= 2 || map[i + 1][j - 1]));
		}
	}
	return map;
}

```

With the memory we can know isPalindrome(s, i, j) in O(1) time by looking at the memory.
Total time complexity is O(n!). If we count for the substring API of java, it would take O(n) time worse cases. A better approach might be using char[] array as input and use the String(char[] array, int offset, int length) constructor.
Total space complexity is O(n^2)

Attached is the full code.

```
class Solution {
    public List<List<String>> partition(String s) {
        List<List<String>> result = new ArrayList<>();
        if (s == null || s.isEmpty()) {
            return result;
        }
        boolean[][] isPalindrome = generateMap(s);
        DFS(0, s, new ArrayList<>(), result, isPalindrome);
        return result;
    }

    private void DFS(int index, String input, List<String> curr, List<List<String>> result, boolean[][] isPalindrome) {
        if (index == input.length()) {
            result.add(new ArrayList<>(curr));
            return;
        }
        for (int i = index; i < input.length(); i++) {
            if (isPalindrome[index][i]) {
                curr.add(input.substring(index, i + 1));
                DFS(i + 1, input, curr, result, isPalindrome);
                curr.remove(curr.size() - 1);
            }
        }
    }

    private boolean[][] generateMap(String s) {
        boolean[][] map = new boolean[s.length()][s.length()];
        for (int i = s.length() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int j = i; j < s.length(); j++) {
                map[i][j] = (s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(j) && (j - i <= 2 || map[i + 1][j - 1]));
            }
        }
        return map;
    }
}
```

