solutions.content:
# Approach 1 (Primality)
To ensure a number is Power of 2, it should have 2 as the only Prime factor. If we can assure this, we can ensure that our Number is Power of 2. This might not work for bigger numbers as we would have to get all factors and check for primality, resulting in very bad time and space complexities.

# Approach 2 (Divisibility)
Numbers that are Power of 2 will be divisible by two unless it reaches 1. So we can keep dividing the number by 2 unless we get 1. If we encounter an remainder in the process, it makes our assumption void and the number isn't a power of 2.
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        while(n>1){
            if(n%2==1){
                return false;
            }
            else{
                n/=2;
            }
        }
        return (n==1);
    }
};
```
# Approach 3 (Math)
Powers of 2, give whole number result on calculating their Logarithm with base 2. So we can use this for our case.
We already rule out cases where n<=0, to avoid mathematical errors.
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        if(n<=0) return false;
        return log2(n)== (int)log2(n);
    }
};
```
# Approach 4 ( Bit Manipulation - I )
Bit Manipulation refers to using the Binary equivalent of a number to get our result. For powers of 2 , we can infer that their Binary representation will always have only one 1. (i.e. one set-bit).
So, we may find the binary and count the number of 1s in the form.
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        if(n<=0)return false; // base condition
        int set_bits=0;
        while(n){
            int r=n%2;
            if(r)set_bits++;
            n/=2;
        }
        return (set_bits==1);
    }
};
```
# Approach 5 (Bit Manipulation II - C++ One liner)
We can use **builtin_popcount()** method given with C++ compiler to directly get the number of set-bits from a given input number.
Using Ternary operator makes it even lesser to code **;-)** 
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        return (n>0?__builtin_popcount(n)==1:false);
    }
};
```
# Approach 6 (Bit Manipulation - III )
Consider any Power of 2, say 8. 
Binary representation of 8 is **1000** .
Now lets see Binary representation of n-1, i.e 7 , which is **0111**
So, on performing N & (N-1), we should have Zero as output if our N is a power of 2.
For any non-power of 2, we will always get a value other than Zero (i.e. 5 & 4 = 4).
So it is a valid test .
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        if(n<=0)
            return false;
        return ((n & (n-1)) == 0);
    }
};
```

