solutions.content:
**Solution 1: Flip Least-Significant Set Bit**

- The operation `n & (n - 1)` flips the least-significant bit in `n`. For example. `1010` will become `1000`
- If `n` is a power of `2` then only one bit of `n` is set. If we clear this least-significant only set bit of `n`, then it will become `0`.
For example- 
```
Let n  =  8  =  1 0 0 0
n - 1  =  7  =  0 1 1 1
then,
n & (n - 1) will result in zero.
```

Time complexity: `O(1)`
Space Complexity: `O(1)`

```
class Solution 
{
    public boolean isPowerOfTwo(int n) 
    {
        return n > 0 && (n & n - 1) == 0;
    }
}
```

**Solution 2: Count Number of Set Bits**

- All power of two numbers have only one bit set. So count the number of set bits and if we get `1` then number is a power of `2`

Time complexity: `O(1)`
Space Complexity: `O(1)`

```
class Solution 
{
    public boolean isPowerOfTwo(int n) 
    {
        return n > 0 && Integer.bitCount(n) == 1;    
    }
}
```

**Solution 3: Repeated Division by Two**

- Here the idea is to keep dividing the number iteratively by two. In any iteration, if `n` becomes `odd` and `n` is not `1` then `n` is not a power of `2`. If `n` becomes `1` then it is a power of `2`.

Time complexity: `O(log n)`
Space Complexity: `O(1)`

```
class Solution 
{
    public boolean isPowerOfTwo(int n) 
    {
        if(n == 0)
            return false;

        while(n % 2 == 0)
            n /= 2;

        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

