If we think about the iterative approach of pre-order traversing a binary tree, whose halting condition is "stack.isEmpty() && currentNode==null", which means "you have done everything && now you have nothing to do" -- a valid pre-order sequence should comply with this.

1. If we meet "#", which means current root (the element at stack top)'s left subtree is done, we should pop this root (--stackSize) and go on traversing its right subtree. If no such root (stackSize == 0), we should stop and check whether we have traversed the entire tree (p == seq.length-1), or we are given an invalid sequence (there are still nodes we have not visited, that is p < seq.length-1).

2. If we meet "some integer", it means we are visiting current root and should push it into our stack (++stackSize) and move on to its left subtree. 


