class Solution {
public:
    bool isValidSerialization(string preorder) {
        int len = preorder.length();
		//difference = sentinel_count - number_count
        int difference = 0;
        for(int i = len - 1; i >= 0; i-=2){
            if(preorder[i] == '#'){
                difference++;
            }
            else{
			    //it's a number, skip all digits
			    while(i >= 1 && preorder[i - 1] != ','){
                    i--;
                }
                difference--;
            }
            if(difference < 1){
                return false;
            }
        }
        return difference == 1;
    }
};
/* 
The idea is based on leaf-vertices deletions (by replacing substr "num,#,#" by "#")
untill the string will become serialization of null root ("#").
If there is no leafs and the string is not equal to "#" the answer is false.
Note that correct serialization always ends with several sentinels.
Let assume it ends with n sentinels (we don't take into account commas) 
and there is m consecutive numbers just before this sentinels. 
Let's start deleting leafs from the end of the string:
we take the last number in the string and two following '#' and replace it by '#'.
Both m and n decremented after this operation. Let's continue.
Note that if m >= n after (n - 1) operations we will get one '#'
in the end of string and at least 1 number just before it.
Current last number can never be deleted if continue deleting leafs
so the answer is false, m should be <= n - 1 if the answer is true.

Let's do this transformtions (consequtive leaf deletion from the end of string) on example:
"9,3,4,#,#,1,#,#,2,#,(6,#,#)" -> "9,3,4,#,#,1,#,#,(2,#,#)" ->
"9,3,4,#,#,(1,#,#),#" -> "9,3,(4,#,#),#,#" -> "9,(3,#,#),#" ->
"(9,#,#)" -> "#" - so the answer is true

As I mentioned before the string is a serialization of tree if at each step the number of '#' 
in the end (n) is at least equals to m + 1 (n >= m + 1), where m is the number
of consequctive numbers just before the sentinels in the end of the string.

So I found out that I can check string without actually deleting the leafs,
I can simply check if difference = sentinel_count - number_count >= 1 all the time
when I scan string from the end. And also I need to check if finally difference = 1.

The difference should be equal 1 after string scanning because during one leaf deletion I 
decrement both numbers_count and sentinel_count. And in the end I should get "#"
if the answer is true.
*/

```

